data.content:
## Migration Analysis

**Pattern identified:** Timeout enforcement + ThreadAbortException as control flow

Your code has three APIs that don't work in .NET 8:

| API | Problem in .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never fires (abort can't be thrown) |

### Root cause

.NET 8 uses **cooperative cancellation** — code must voluntarily check for cancellation. The runtime will not forcibly inject an exception into a running thread.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(), token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Preferred: async overload
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        try
        {
            return await work(token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | `Task.WaitAsync` detaches the *waiter*, but the delegate keeps running on the thread pool. The old `Thread.Abort` killed it; cooperative cancellation cannot. If `work()` is a tight CPU loop, it runs to completion in the background. |
| **Fix for the above** | Accept `Func<CancellationToken, T>` and require callers to check the token (use the async overload as the model). Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints inside work. |
| **CancellationTokenSource leaks** | Always wrap in `using`. Leaking it leaks internal timers. |
| **Don't swallow OperationCanceledException** | Only catch it at this top-level orchestration point to convert to `TimeoutException`. Let it propagate everywhere else. |
| **Blocking on async (`GetAwaiter().GetResult()`)** | The sync overload can deadlock in UI/ASP.NET contexts with a `SynchronizationContext`. Prefer the async overload. |

### If the work truly can't cooperate

If `work()` calls code you don't control (e.g., a native library), no in-process mechanism can kill it. Move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`:

```csharp
var process = Process.Start("worker.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

This is the only reliable replacement for the old `Thread.Abort` "kill it now" semantics.
